(698, 'event', '68', 'comment', 'EN', '  When France fell in June 1940 there were many French civilians and military personnel in the United Kingdom, including those returning from missions in Norway.  Most of these chose to return to occupied or Vichy France whilst a small  number remained in Britain with the intention of contributing to the liberation of their homeland.\r\n\r\nVery quickly their numbers were reinforced by a steady flow of evadees from occupied france, often via Spanish prisons, or by small boat from Britanny.  Many were responding to the call of General de Gaulle to continue the fight for freedom from Britain.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '*', '2003-03-24 13:30:28'),
(699, 'event', '69', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>In July 1941 De Gaulle was eager,despite its small size, that the Free French should participate fully and would take paret in the fighting in the Near-East.  As well the wish to show Free France playing an active role in the war there was also a desire to ensure that as ex French territories became liberated they did not become annexed by Britain.  To this end he asked for the 1 C.P. to be moved out to Lebanon.  At this time, Syria and Lebanon had just been liberated by the Allies. Most of the 1st CIA were sent to Glasgow where they joined the troop ship Cameronia on 21st July.  After a long sea voyage around the Cape with a change of ship at Durban, the company eventuaty arrive at Beiruit in September after two months at sea.</p>', 'David Portier', '2013-12-15 14:24:20'),
(700, 'event', '69', 'comment', 'FR', '<p >Juillet 1941, le général de Gaulle tient particulièrement, malgré son petit nombre, à ce que la France Libre soit présente partout et participe aux combats du Proche-Orient. Il souhaite ainsi faire la preuve que la France Libre occupe un rôle actif dans la conduite de la guerre et également s\'assurer que les territoires français libérés ne seront pas alors dirigés par les Britanniques. Dans ce but, il réclame donc que la 1re CP soit envoyée au Levant. A cette date, la Syrie et le Liban viennent d\'être libéré par les Alliés.</p><p ><br></p><p >Le 21 juillet 1941, la majorité des éléments de la 1re CP embarquent à Greenock à bord du transport de troupes S/S Cameronia. Le convoi prend la mer le 3 août et atteint Freetown le 17 puis Capetown le 2 septembre. Le 5 septembre, les hommes font escale à Durban puis embarquent sur le S/S New Amsterdam. Le convoi CM 18 atteint Suez le 18 septembre.</p><p >A la suite d\'un long périple, la Compagnie atteint enfin Beyrouth le 23 septembre après deux mois en mer.</p>', 'David P', '2019-09-26 11:55:39'),
(701, 'event', '70', 'comment', 'EN', 'Following the request for an Armistice made by maréchal Pétain the previous day, général de Gaulle made an appeal over the BBC to the French people. He asked them to join him in England to continue the fight for freedom.', '*', '2003-04-06 09:12:43'),
(702, 'event', '71', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>After parachute training, the 1 C.I.A was installed at Exbury in the training camp at Inchmery House, situate on the coast facing the Isle of Wight. The company was then renamed 1ère Compagnie Parachutiste and then included 10 officers, 12 NCOs and 74 men. There the parachutists received an advanced and physically demanding commando training.<br />Two distinct groups were set up. The first received combat training including training in unarmed combat. The second was destined for undercover work and espionage.<br />At the end of June, Général de Gaulle ordered the 1st CP to Syria. Capitaine Bergé left behind at Inchmery the undercover specialist. On the 16th July, the rest of the unit arrived at London and spent several days in a transit camp at Barnes.</p>\r\n<p>List of French parachutists known to be present at Exbury in may 1941 :</p>', 'David Portier', '2017-07-29 10:43:06'),
(703, 'event', '72', 'comment', 'EN', ' The target of the second mission was to destroy a power station at Pressac supplying a submarine base near Bordeaux.  Le Tac was to join the stick when they were dropped in France on the night of the 11th May.   The operation, supported by a group of resistance who had been set up by Berge during the Savanah operation, when he took time to visit his family home near Bordeaux, was a success and the power station was destroyed.  The stick returned to the UK via Spain in July 1941.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(704, 'event', '73', 'comment', 'EN', ' The 1CIA arrived in the Levant on 23th September 1941.  The Syrian war was over and the bulk of the Army of the Levant had returned to occupied France.  There were however many Free French from the Colonial troups who were waiting to join the emerging Free French Forces.  As the main encounters with the enemy were currently in North Africa there was no plans to move these forces to other theatres of war.  There were airforce squadrons, Foreign Legion battalions and other land forces groups recruiting and training in the region.   \r\n\r\nBerge was activily trying to recruit into his young Company, as well as to find training facilities and, of course, a mission to enable them to engage with the enemy.   Training facilities for parachuting were non existent,  learning to roll off moving lorries was one improvisation.  During this period there were losses from parachute and explosives training.  Gaultier died on Christmas eve as a result of an acident with explosives.\r\n\r\nThe Company was based at Meze the airfield of Damascus.\r\n\r\nEventually the french forces were authorised to colaborate with British forces and a consolidation took place with many soldiers moving from the Levant to Egypt.   Berge obtained pernission to integrate his company with the SAS battalion being formed by Stirling at Kabret on the Suex canal.', '*', '2003-04-10 04:54:05'),
(705, 'event', '74', 'comment', 'EN', 'On Christmas eve 1941 Gaultier was killed during an explosives training session.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(706, 'event', '75', 'comment', 'EN', 'Three of the company were killed during a training flight together with the pilot Newman.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(707, 'event', '76', 'comment', 'EN', 'General de Gaulle supported by Churchill, became the beacon for those who refused to accept defeat.  The HQ of the Free French was established at St Stephens House in London, this was the destination for those French men and women arriving at London who wanted to continue the fight.  \r\n\r\nAmong these was Capitain George Berge.  Wounded during the defence of France he was recovering in hospital when he learned of the armistice. The 19th of June, he succeeded in boarding a boat at St_Jean de Luz and arrived in Great Brittain the 23rd of June.  The next day he reported for duty to Stephen House. Having briefy been a member of a parachute company in 1937, he saw the value of parachutists in the eventual liberation of France and lobbied de Gaulle for permission to create a parachute company.  On 15 September 1940 the 1ère Compagnie de l\'Infanterie de l\'Air was established with Bergé in command.', '*', '2003-04-06 09:29:46'),
(708, 'event', '77', 'comment', 'EN', 'When the the 1st CIA left for the Near-East, a small number of men under the command of capitaine René Weill Ã‚Â« Georges Ã‚Â» remained in England aand were transfered to the  Old Dean Camp near Camberley.  Some were posted to the B.C.R.A, the French intelligence services or worked with the British Special Operations Executive (SOE). In May capitaine Weill was sent on a mission in France.  Capitaine Coulet then commanded the Infanterie de l\'Air at Camberley until December 1942.  Little by little, new voluntiers managed to reach Britain and enlisted in the Free French parachiutists.', 'david', '2008-03-10 19:49:01'),
(709, 'event', '78', 'comment', 'EN', 'The first mission after training of the 1 CIA was to be dropped into Britanny near Vannes.  The intention was to attack a bus carrying German aircrew who were harrassing Allied shipping in the Channel.  Unfortunately the crews were relocated to the base and the daily trip no longer took place.  Berge and Forman returned by submarine on the 5th April. Le Tac remaining in France.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(710, 'event', '79', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>The French SAS (1BIA) paraded in London on Bastille day 1943. The banner was carried by Victor Itturia flanked by Jean Le Gall and Jean Roquemaure.</p>', 'paul golder', '2013-12-02 10:21:32'),
(711, 'event', '86', 'comment', 'EN', 'In May 1944 the SAS battalions were transported by train from Scotland  to Fairford in Gloucestershire.  This became the secret airfield from which they were to be flown into France whan the invasion was launched.  All leave was cancelled and final preparations commenced.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(712, 'event', '87', 'comment', 'EN', 'After a year in the Middle east and North Africa, at the end of march 1943, the group under S/Lt Martin also arrived having finished the war in North Africa.  They arrived at Liverpool before the main returners who were sailing around the cape.', '*', '2003-05-25 10:09:29'),
(713, 'event', '88', 'comment', 'EN', 'To be recognised Free French you had to have signed an engagement before the 1st August 1943.', 'David Portier', '2005-12-18 06:03:13'),
(714, 'event', '89', 'comment', 'EN', 'The French SAS batalions had important roles assigned to them in support of the invasion.   In Traditional SAS fashion they were to be dropped behind enemy lines and through sabotage, ambush and organising the internal resistance disrupt and distract the occupying forces from reaching the Normandy front.  Then they were to faciliate the advance of the main liberation forces.  Being lightly armed they were not in a position to engage in the sort of fixed battles that the invasion force was fighting.  4SAS was dropped in force into Britanny, whilst 3SAS followed and was launched on a number of missions across the middle of France.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(715, 'event', '90', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the war in France drew to a close the SAS were gathered at bases in the Champagne at Montmirail and Eperney. In free Paris on Armistice day 1944 the SAS paraded down the Champs Elysees. They were led by Lt/Col Bourgoin with Lt Legrand carrying the SAS flag. In front of the Arc de Triomphe General De Gaulle presented the 2nd RCP (4SAS) with the Croix de Compagnon de la Liberation. This was the first time that the regiment as a whole had worn the red beret. Following the end of action in France a certain amount of change hit the SAS. Many of the senior officers including Bourgoin were given other responsibiliteis and Puech Samson took command of the 4 SAS and Conan the 3rd.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(716, 'event', '91', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>From the 15th of June 3SAS started to arrive in France.  From the west coast to Lyon and the Rhone valley all the main arteries which the enemy might use to retreat or consolidate were the target of SAS activity.</p>', 'paul golder', '2012-09-19 03:02:58'),
(717, 'event', '92', 'comment', 'EN', 'The intention was to drop 4 SAS into Brittany on the night before D-day.  The first two groups were to set up operational centres and then receive and distribute arms to the resistance or FFI (Force Française Intérieur).  The SAS and FFI were to jointly harass the German troops in Brittany and impede them from joining the Normandy front.  In the short term there was also a possibility that the Germans would be mislead into thinking than another invasion front was being opened up in Brittany.', '*', '2003-06-21 01:15:41'),
(718, 'event', '93', 'comment', 'EN', 'The 2nd Company 3 SAS were brought back to Britain on the 22 August 1944 and were then despatched in two waves to undertake operations in the East of France.  The objective being to establish a base in the Doubs on the Suisse frontier to support the local resistance in order to slow down as much as possible the enemy retreat.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(719, 'event', '101', 'comment', 'EN', '', 'david', '2009-07-18 17:24:41'),
(720, 'event', '102', 'comment', 'EN', ' The landings in Provence occured on the 15th of August.  With a mission similar to that in Britanny, the SAS were landed in the Rhone valley to impede the retreating enemy and facilate the advance of the allied forces.  Progress was better than expected with Lyon being liberated on the 3rd of September, whereas the allies had expected this to take until the 15th November.  It was the 14th of September that the southern liberating forces met up with those coming from Normandy.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(721, 'event', '103', 'comment', 'EN', ' These missions were intended to inflict maximum losses on the retrerating enemy along the main axes north the RN6 and the RN74.  The sticks were dropped near Sarlrney, Savigny and Messey and  established bases in the Maconais.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(722, 'event', '106', 'comment', 'EN', ' A reconnaisance mission in the Compiegne region led by Lt Kirschen of the Belge SAS.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(723, 'event', '119', 'comment', 'EN', 'Arrivals in June, July 1944 etc.', '*', '2003-05-18 02:14:37'),
(724, 'event', '120', 'comment', 'EN', '&lt;p align=justify&gt;On the night of the 7/8 th June 1944 eighteen small groups from 4 SAS were parachuted into Britany to carry out specific sabotage missions.  Dropped blind without a welcoming committee they were expected to operate without contacting local residents for 48 hours while they carried out their principal mission, usually destruction of railway lines.  After this they were to remain active for 8 to 10 days with secondary missions, destruction of other communications, depots, power lines etc, as well as impeding the repair of the original target.  The groups were then to regroup on the northern or southern base Samwest or Dingson.    After the destruction of the Samwest base (12/13 June) , groups were alerted to report to Dingson.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If the invasion was abandoned, the message *les carrottes sont cuites* would alert them to make for the coast where ferries would return them to to Britain ', 'paul', '2008-03-10 00:24:28'),
(725, 'event', '128', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick sabote la voie ferrée entre Messac et Châteaubriant avant de rejoindre la base Dingson.', '*', '2003-06-27 09:56:01'),
(726, 'event', '129', 'comment', 'EN', '* Le stick est parachuté en Loire-Inférieure près de Saint-Gildas des Bois pour saboter la ligne de Redon à  Pontchâteau puis ils rejoignent la base Dingson.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:03:00'),
(727, 'event', '130', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick opère près de Rochefort-en-Terre et sabote la ligne Redon-Questembert avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 09:58:08'),
(728, 'event', '131', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick opère vers Elven et coupe la ligne Questembert-Vannes avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 09:58:26'),
(729, 'event', '132', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le groupe opère entre Ploërmel et Messac avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 09:58:43'),
(730, 'event', '133', 'comment', 'EN', ' *Le stick est parachuté près de Malestroit dans le but de saboter la voie ferrée entre Ploërmel et Questembert puis les trois parachutistes rejoignent la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 10:02:08'),
(731, 'event', '134', 'comment', 'EN', ' *Le stick est parachuté près de Baud pour saboter la ligne Auray-Pontivy avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 10:01:08'),
(732, 'event', '135', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>*Le stick sabote la voie ferrée Saint-Méen - Ploërmel avant d\'encadrer des maquisards dans la région de Ploermel</p>', 'David Portier', '2016-01-30 10:06:45'),
(733, 'event', '136', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick sabote la voie ferrée entre Loudéac et Merdrignac puis encadre des maquisards dans ce secteur.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:03:43'),
(734, 'event', '137', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick sabote la ligne de Saint-Brieuc à  Loudéac avant de rejoindre le secteur de Gomené.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:04:13'),
(735, 'event', '138', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le groupe coupe la ligne Loudéac - Rostrenen puis opère dans la région de Corlay et participe à  la libération de Paimpol.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:04:38'),
(736, 'event', '139', 'comment', 'EN', 'Open up the route for the 3rd division US infantry by harrasing the enemy garrisions between Morlaix and Brest and impeding the reinforment of the Brest garrison from the east.  Protect the viaducs of Morlaix and Plougastel and to support the resistance.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(737, 'event', '151', 'comment', 'EN', ' Sabotage of railway lines in the South West from Nates to La Rochelle.  Harassment of the enemy, organisation of the resistance and finally holding the nothern front of the enemy pocket at La Rochelle.   ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(738, 'event', '160', 'comment', 'FR', '<p align=justify>Depuis près d\'un an, le Lt Marienne entraîne ses hommes pour ce moment tant attendu de pouvoir, le premier, fouler le sol de France en libérateur.\r\n<br>Il est 00h30 le 6 juin 1944 et à  travers le trou du Stirling, le dispatcher regarde défiler la campagne bretonne. La lumière est au rouge, \"Action - Station\".\r\n<br>Les hommes du stick Marienne se lèvent et accrochent la sangle de leur parachute à  la static line qui traverse l\'avion.\r\n<br>Soudain, le pilote découvre les repères et la proximité de la DZ. La lumière passe au vert. \"Go!\"', 'David Portier', '2006-10-16 12:35:48'),
(739, 'event', '330', 'comment', 'FR', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Le groupe du lieutenant Marienne touche terre à 00h45 à  deux kilomètres de l\'endroit prévu, dans les landes à  l\'est du hameau de Halliguen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sans le savoir, les parachutistes français sont tombés à  huit cents mètres du Moulin de la Grée à  Plumelec, transformé en poste d\'observation par les Allemands.<br />Aussitôt, l\'alerte est donnée et un détachement de Géorgiens se lance à  la recherche des SAS. <br /><br />Tandis qu\'une partie du stick est à  la recherche de la malle en osier du capitaine André Hunter-Hue alias Fernand, agent du SOE parachuté avec les SAS, le caporal Bouétard et l\'équipe radio sont encerclés. Rapidement, Emile Bouétard est blessé et achevé par l\'ennemi alors que Jordan, Etrich et Sauvé sont faits prisonniers.<br /><br />Au bruit des combats, le stick se disperse. Tandis que le lieutenant Marienne, Louis et Krysik décrochent vers le sud, traversent La Claie et rejoignent la Petite-Métairie, le Sgt/C Raufast et le capitaine André partent vers Saint-Jean-Brévelay.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-10-13 11:14:18'),
(740, 'event', '162', 'comment', 'EN', ' A standard 2nd SAS mission dropped to the SE of Vtre to collect information on enmey movements and to harrass them.', 'David Portier', '2006-05-22 11:51:11'),
(741, 'event', '163', 'comment', 'EN', ' The stick, led by Captain Lee 2SAS was parachuted to the South of Paris in July with the objective of capturing Rommel.', 'David Portier', '2006-03-17 14:49:53'),
(742, 'event', '164', 'comment', 'EN', '<p align=justify>Deplante was charged by Bourgoin to set up a northern base to replace the lost Samwest base.  The was to receive redistribute and then co-ordinate the work of SAS and resistance coming from the overrun Dingson base and the Duault(Samwest) bases.', 'David Portier', '2006-09-14 14:08:34'),
(743, 'event', '165', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the liberating forces gained a substantial foothold in Normandy and the enemy forces in Britany were being defeated, the SAS were being required to operate further east.  To supply adequate transport a major delivery of jeeps was made, by parachute and by gliders under the noses of the occupation forces in Vannes.  Betbeze. Paoli, Itturia and the reserve 4SAS arrived with the jeeps near Mallachappe.  There was a certain impatiance in these forces having missed the first two months of the liberation, however the enemy were far from defeated and much of France was still occupied so there was still work to be done. ', 'david', '2009-06-16 18:24:21'),
(744, 'event', '166', 'comment', 'EN', ' Harassing the enemy facilitating the progress of alied forces arriving from the south. ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(745, 'event', '167', 'comment', 'EN', '<p><br></p>', 'David P', '2020-04-03 08:48:06'),
